[4] South Sudan
Date: Wed 28 Jun 2017
Source: Sudan Tribune [edited]
http://www.sudantribune.com/spip.php?article62853


Lack of funds needed to train vaccinators caused the deaths of 16 children during the botched measles vaccination campaign in South Sudan, an official said on Tue [27 Jun 2017].

"The measles campaign was carried out by UNICEF [UN Children's Emergency Fund] with the World Health Organization and Ministry of Health. When we asked for funding to train nurses and volunteers who were to administer the vaccines, there was no funding from UNICEF," Kapoeta state governor Luis Lobong told the Council of States.

35 children, who received the measles vaccine, fell ill in Kapeota.

Last month [May 2017], South Sudan's health minister, Riek Gai Kok attributed the bizarre incident to what he described as typical "human error."

However, while appearing before the country's lawmakers on Tue [27 Jun 2017], Gai explained that steps were being taken by the health ministry, WHO and UNICEF to ensure mistakes [do not] occur again.

"We regret the death of the 15 children, who showed the same symptoms after being vaccinated with measles [vaccine]. The health volunteers were not trained, and they mistakenly used one syringe to [vaccinate] many children. We sincerely extend our condolences to the families and the victims of this mistake," said Gai.

Unconfirmed reports say children as young as 10 years participated as volunteers to administer measles vaccines in the botched campaigns in Kapoeta, despite the lack of electric power to moderate the vaccine's temperature as well as poor handling of medical sets.

South Sudanese lawmakers, however, demanded justice for families affected, yet some citizens wanted those officials concerned to be impeached for their alleged failure to provide proper leadership.

South Sudan is acknowledged to have some of the worst health indicators in the world.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The deaths of the vaccinated children were completely avoidable. Surely, if public health officials were giving the vaccine to the children, they should know best practices to preserve the safety of the vaccination process, i.e., the importance of changing needles between individuals. It is difficult to imagine that children "as young as 10" who would not have that expertise were allowed to give vaccinations.

Maps of South Sudan can be seen at https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b0/28_States_of_South_Sudan.png and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5145654,8402. - Mod.LK]

